  "prompt": "If black holes pull in all matter due to a high gravitational pull, but light has no mass and also isn't considered matter, how can black holes exist?",
  "response": "This is a great question that touches on some fascinating aspects of gravity and general relativity. Here's the breakdown:\n\n**1. It's Not Just About Mass: Gravity and Spacetime**\n\n*   **Newtonian Gravity (the \"Pull\" idea):** In the classical Newtonian view, gravity is a force proportional to mass. More mass = more gravitational force. This is a good approximation for many everyday situations.\n\n*   **Einstein's General Relativity (Spacetime Distortion):** Einstein revolutionized our understanding of gravity. General relativity says that gravity isn't a force in the traditional sense. Instead, **gravity is the curvature of spacetime caused by mass and energy.**\n\n    *   **Spacetime:** Imagine a fabric woven from the three dimensions of space (length, width, height) and the dimension of time.\n    *   **Mass/Energy Warps Spacetime:** Massive objects (and, importantly, energy) warp or distort this spacetime fabric.\n    *   **Objects Follow Curves:** Objects (and light!) then follow the curves created by this warped spacetime. So, it's not that a massive object is pulling everything in, it's creating a \"well\" in spacetime, and things \"fall\" into that well.\n\n**2. How Black Holes Form and Their Extreme Spacetime Distortion**\n\n*   **Stellar Collapse:** Black holes typically form when massive stars (much larger than our sun) run out of fuel at the end of their lives. The star's core collapses under its own immense gravity.\n\n*   **Extreme Curvature:** The collapse concentrates an enormous amount of mass into an incredibly small volume. This creates an extremely deep \"well\" in spacetime.\n\n*   **Event Horizon:** The boundary of this well is called the **event horizon**. It's the point of no return. Anything that crosses the event horizon, even light, is trapped. This is because the spacetime curvature within the event horizon is so extreme that all paths lead to the center of the black hole.\n\n**3. Light and Black Holes**\n\n*   **Light Follows Spacetime:** Light, though massless, *does* follow the curvature of spacetime. This is a key prediction of general relativity that has been experimentally confirmed.\n*   **No Escape:** When light gets close enough to a black hole, the curvature of spacetime is so severe that the path light would normally take is bent back toward the black hole's center. It cannot escape past the event horizon.\n\n**Analogy:**\n\nThink of a bowling ball placed on a trampoline. The bowling ball creates a dip. If you roll a marble (light) nearby, the marble will curve towards the bowling ball because of the dip in the trampoline's surface.  A black hole is like an incredibly heavy bowling ball creating a very deep, inescapable dip.\n\n**In Summary**\n\nBlack holes exist because they represent an extreme warping of spacetime. Light, even though it has no mass, is affected by this warping. If light gets too close, it can't escape because the curvature of spacetime within the event horizon directs all paths toward the black hole's center. The \"pull\" of a black hole isn't just about mass attracting other mass; it's about the geometry of spacetime being drastically altered.\n\n",
